## Migration: `TimedExecutor` to .NET 8

### Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Effectively dead — never raised |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state by injecting exceptions at arbitrary points (mid-write, mid-lock, etc.).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative cancellation timeout.
    /// Callers must observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> passed to <paramref name="work"/>.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules on the thread pool — no manual Thread needed
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Overload for async work
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// The lambda MUST check the token — cancellation is cooperative
string result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // <-- critical
        // ... do work ...
    }
    return "done";
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async version
var data = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    // Most BCL APIs accept CancellationToken natively
    return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

### Key Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.**
Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation only works if the delegate **checks the token**. If you call third-party code that ignores the token, it will keep running. For truly untrusted code, run it out-of-process.

**2. Don't use `task.Wait(timeout)` as a drop-in.**
It returns `bool` but leaves the task running in the background — a fire-and-forget resource leak.

**3. `AggregateException` wrapping changed.**
`Task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` throws the inner exception directly (not wrapped in `AggregateException`), which differs from the original code's explicit wrapping.

**4. `Task.Run` uses the thread pool.**
The original created a dedicated thread. For long-running CPU work, pass `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning` to `Task.Factory.StartNew` instead — but note it doesn't return `Task<T>` directly from `Task.Run`.

**5. `WaitAsync` (used in the async overload) is .NET 6+.**
It ensures the `await` returns promptly on timeout even if the underlying task hasn't completed — exactly what you want.
